1. (20 points) Merging and Imputation

Merging

The two datasets (individual and regional CHS datasets) were merged by town name, and there are no duplicates; this is confirmed by the number of rows in merged dataset (\(n_{merged}\) = 1200) is equaled to the number of rows in the individual CHS dataset (\(n_{individual}\) = 1200).

Imputation

Missing data was shown in the several numeric and categorical variables. Following the instruction, the observations were divided four groups (male, hispanic), (male, non-hispanic), (female, hispanic), and (female, non-hispanic); then, the missing values of numeric data were replaced by their own group average.

For the catergorical data, the mode function was used. This function is in DescTools package. Under the mode, the missing values were replaced by the most frequently occurring category.

# Imputation
# continuous variables (double type)
num_vars <- names(merged)[sapply(merged, is.double)]

# categorical integer variables
cat_vars <- names(merged)[sapply(merged, is.integer)]

# height and weight integer but continuous data. 
num_vars <- union(num_vars, c("height", "weight"))
cat_vars <- setdiff(cat_vars, c("height", "weight"))

# Remove grouping variables (Grouping variable does not have missing data)
# confirmation - no missing data in grouping variables
sum(is.na(merged$male))
[1] 0
sum(is.na(merged$hispanic))
[1] 0
num_vars <- setdiff(num_vars, c("male", "hispanic"))
cat_vars <- setdiff(cat_vars, c("male", "hispanic"))

## Impute continuous data by average
merged <- merged %>%
  group_by(male, hispanic) %>%
  mutate(across(all_of(num_vars),
                ~ replace(., is.na(.), mean(., na.rm = TRUE)))) %>%
  ungroup()
print(head(merged), width = Inf)

2.(10 points) A new categorical variable, âobesity_levelâ and its summary table

Following the instruction, new category was created with criteria (underweight BMI<14; normal BMI 14-22; overweight BMI 22-24; obese BMI>24). Summary table with Min BMI, Max BMI and total number of observations per category was also generated.

merged <- merged %>%
  mutate(obesity_level = case_when(
    bmi < 14 ~ "Underweight",
    bmi >= 14 & bmi < 22 ~ "Normal",
    bmi >= 22 & bmi < 24 ~ "Overweight",
    bmi >= 24 ~ "Obese"
  ))

summary_table <- merged %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarise(
    Min_BMI = min(bmi),
    Max_BMI = max(bmi),
    n = n()
  )
print(head(merged$obesity_level))

4. (10 points) Four summary tables: Fev by town, sex, obesity level, and smoke_gas_exposure

Four summary tables about âForced expiratory volume in 1 second (ml)â (fev: an asthma indicator) by town, sex, obesity level, and âsmoke_gas_exposure.â

Comments

  1. fev vs town: The average of fev ranges from 1985.202 ml (Mira Loma) to 2087.101 ml (Alpine) with about 100 ml of difference. Standard deviations are 277~351 ml. There is a town-level variation in lung capacity but because of big variance, but more analysis is needed to determine it is meaningful.

  2. fev vs gender The average of fev is 1959 ml (s.d 311.9181 ml) in female and 2104 ml (s.d 307.5123 ml) for male with with about 145 ml of the average difference. Average is different between geneder indicating females have bigger lung capacity, and standard deviations are very similar.

  3. fev vs obesity The average of fev ranges from 1698 ml (underweight) to 2266 ml (obese) with about 570 ml of the difference. The average of fev is getting increase when obesity level is getting higher. Especially, underweight individuals have considerablely low fev. Standard deviations are 295 ~325 ml.

  4. fev vs smoke&gas exposure: There average of fev ranges from 2022.671 ml (gas) to 2056.693 ml (none) with about 35 ml of difference. Standard deviations are about 295 ~ 329 ml. There is unlikely to have association of fev with any of four categories because of these small differences and standard deviation range. This suggests that second hand smoke or gas stove are unlikely to affect lung capacity.

In summary, lung capacity measured by Forced expiratory volume decreased remarkably when obese level is getting lower. Geographical variation and gender variation are also observed but the statistical significance is needed to be analyzed more. Interestingly, the second hand smoking or gas exposure unlikely affect lung capacity.

Looking at the Data (EDA) (20 points)

EDA check

  • bmi, fev, smoke_gas_exposure and pm25_mass are the variables of interests.

  • Real data range by google

    • BMI: about 15 ~ over 40

    • FEV: about 1500 ~ 4500 ml

    • smoke_gas_exposure: N/A (categorical data)

    • PM2.5_mass: about 0 ~ 35 ug/m^3 (Unhealthy > 35 ug/m^3)

Observation from EDA check

There are no significantly odd outliers in the four variables of interests.

  • BMI - The distribution is left-skewed. Population seems underweighted. Mean is marginal value of healthy weight range and medium is in underweight level.

  • FEV - The distribution has a nice bell-shape with about 2000 ml of average. However, by google search, the typical ranges of heathy people 2500 ml ~ 4500 ml. This also indicate that the population of this data has less lung capacity.

  • PM2.5 - The level of all data were less than moderate range, however, the minimum value is too high comparing the data we analyzed in HW1. There is a possibility that the measurement technology USC used may not be sensitive enough. Other possibility is this data can be collected in long time ago when the sensitive technology was not commonly available as we saw in 2015 data in Michigan state air pollution dataset.

Questions

  1. What is the association between BMI and FEV (forced expiratory volume)?

    • The correlation is 0.357 indicating a weak positive association between BMI and FEV. This weak association also can be observed in the scatter plot.

  2. What is the association between smoke and gas exposure and FEV?

    • There is no association between smoke and gas exposure and FEV. The box size and line position in the box plot are very similar over categories.

  3. What is the association between PM2.5 exposure and FEV?

    • There is no association between PM2.5 exposure and FEV. The mean line does not have significant slop indicating no association.
